{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598350"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:37:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:37:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15468"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15468"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.11,0.06,0.02,0.72]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8159"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61500"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8159"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15468"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46951"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4900"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8130"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19766"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19769"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61500"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETetralogy of Fallot is a congenital heart condition characterised by four anatomical defects.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a component of Tetralogy of Fallot?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Left ventricular hypertrophy","Left-to-right shunt","Pulmonary trunk overriding the ventricular septum","Two atrial septal defects","Ventricular septal defect"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETetralogy of Fallot is characterised by four main defects: a \u003Cstrong\u003Eventricular septal defect\u003C/strong\u003E, pulmonary stenosis, right ventricular hypertrophy, and an overriding aorta. The presence of a ventricular septal defect allows deoxygenated blood to bypass the lungs and enter the systemic circulation, contributing to the cyanosis seen in affected individuals. \u003Cstrong\u003ELeft ventricular hypertrophy\u003C/strong\u003E is not a feature of Tetralogy of Fallot; instead, right ventricular hypertrophy is present due to increased pressure from pulmonary stenosis. A \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft-to-right shunt\u003C/strong\u003E is not typical of Tetralogy of Fallot, as the condition usually involves a right-to-left shunt. The \u003Cstrong\u003Epulmonary trunk overriding the ventricular septum\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect; it is the aorta that overrides the ventricular septum. \u003Cstrong\u003ETwo atrial septal defects\u003C/strong\u003E are not part of Tetralogy of Fallot, which involves a single ventricular septal defect.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Tetralogy of Fallot consists of four key features: ventricular septal defect, pulmonary stenosis, right ventricular hypertrophy, and overriding aorta.","The right-to-left shunt in Tetralogy of Fallot results in deoxygenated blood entering systemic circulation."],"references":["Bailliard F, Anderson RH. Tetralogy of Fallot. Orphanet J Rare Dis. 2009 Jan 13;4:2. doi: 10.1186/1750-1172-4-2. PMID: 19144126; PMCID: PMC2651859","Wilson R, Ross O, Griksaitis MJ. Tetralogy of Fallot. BJA Educ. 2019 Nov;19(11):362-369. doi: 10.1016/j.bjae.2019.07.003. Epub 2019 Oct 14. PMID: 33456859; PMCID: PMC7807827","Alkashkari W, Al-Husayni F, Almaqati A, AlRahimi J, Albugami S. An Adult Patient With a Tetralogy of Fallot Case. Cureus. 2020 Nov 23;12(11):e11658. doi: 10.7759/cureus.11658. PMID: 33391897; PMCID: PMC7769492","Topol, E. J., \u0026 Califf, R. M. (Eds.). (2007). Textbook of cardiovascular medicine. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46951"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15468"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/46951"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-15T16:36:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T16:38:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8159"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61500"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4900"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Card